   <abstract >By employing an organic theory that views theatre as a living body, this thesis explores how theatre has adapted to pandemics throughout history. It suggests that theatre, like the human body and mind, operates as a complex adaptive system, evolving in response to crises. The study examines three historical pandemics—the Athenian Plague, the Spanish Influenza, and COVID-19— through the theatre-as-body framework, highlighting theatre's resilience and healing role in society. This exploration reveals two remarkable adaptations within the theatre-as-body's immune system: catharsis as a purgative release, allowing audiences to emotionally cleanse themselves of collective trauma, and disavowal as a protective mechanism, enabling the theatrical space to momentarily distance spectators from the harsh realities and uncertainties of pandemics. This thesis emphasizes theatre's ability to creatively respond to challenging circumstances and, therefore, reinforce its cultural function.</abstract>
